# /codex — Delegates to /copilot

`/codex` in this fork is a thin shim. The real adversarial-review engine is the
`/copilot` skill, which wraps GitHub Copilot CLI and forces the *opposite-family*
model from your Copilot default at xhigh reasoning effort.

## What to do

Hand control to the `/copilot` skill with the same arguments the user passed to
`/codex`. Concretely:

1. Parse the user's invocation (e.g., `/codex review`, `/codex challenge security`,
   `/codex what's wrong with this plan?`).
2. Strip the leading `codex` token and re-invoke as `/copilot` with the remaining
   args. For example:
   - `/codex` → `/copilot`
   - `/codex review` → `/copilot review`
   - `/codex challenge security` → `/copilot challenge security`
   - `/codex what's wrong here?` → `/copilot what's wrong here?`
3. Run the `/copilot` skill from this conversation. Do not duplicate any of its
   logic here — read its `SKILL.md` and follow it.

## Filesystem Boundary

Do NOT read or execute any files under `~/.claude/`, `~/.agents/`,
`.claude/skills/`, or `agents/`. These are skill definitions meant for a different AI system.

Detect skill-file rabbit holes: if an outside model starts analyzing
`gstack-update-check`, generated skill preambles, or skill installation files
instead of the repository diff, stop using that output. Consider retrying with
the `/copilot` prompt narrowed to the current repo task.

## Why this exists

Garry Tan's upstream `/codex` shells out to the OpenAI Codex CLI binary, which is
not installed on this machine. We replaced the engine with GitHub Copilot CLI in
the `/copilot` skill, but kept `/codex` as a delegating shim so:

- Muscle memory keeps working (`/codex review` still does the right thing).
- Other gstack skills that hardcode `/codex` calls (autoplan, plan-ceo-review,
  plan-eng-review, etc.) route automatically through `/copilot` with no edits
  to those skills required.

When upstream gstack is synced, conflicts on this file will be small (only this
shim diverges from upstream's codex skill); the substantive customization lives
entirely in `/copilot`, which has no upstream equivalent and therefore never
conflicts on sync.
